subsection.p:
As we stated earlier, a rational function is a quotient of two polynomials. Some examples of rational functions are shown below.


		f(x)\amp=\frac{2}{(x-3)^2}\amp\amp\amp g(x)\amp=\frac{x}{x+1}


		h(x)\amp=\frac{2x^2}{x^2+4}\amp\amp\amp k(x)\amp=\frac{x^2-1}{x^2-9}


Because we cannot divide by zero, a rational function f(x) = \displaystyle{\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}} is undefined for any value x = a where Q(a) = 0. These x-values are not in the domain of the function.

solution.p:
This function is undefined for x = 3, so there is no point on the graph with x-coordinate 3. However, we can make a table of values for other values of x. Plotting the ordered pairs in the table results in the points shown in .
x y
0 \dfrac{2}{9}
1 \dfrac{1}{2}
2 2
3 undefined
4 2
4 \dfrac{1}{2}
6 \dfrac{2}{9}
graph showing 6 points about a vertical asymptote
Next, we make a table showing x-values close to 3, as in a. As we choose x-values closer and closer to 3, (x - 3)^2 gets closer to 0, so the fraction \dfrac{2}{(x-3)^2} gets very large. This means that the graph approaches, but never touches, the vertical line x=3. In other words, the graph has a vertical asymptote at x=3. We indicate the vertical asymptote by a dashed line, as shown in b. table of values and graph of rational function

li.p:
On the trip from Dallas to Phoenix, the plane encounters a headwind of 30 miles per hour, so its actual ground speed is r-30. On the return trip, the plane enjoys a tailwind of 30 miles per hour, so its actual ground speed is r+30. Therefore, the flying times are

	\text{Dallas to Phoenix:}\hphantom{blank}\frac{800}{r-30}

and

	\text{Phoenix to Dallas:}\hphantom{blank}\frac{800}{r+30}

The round-trip flying time from Dallas to Phoenix and back is

	F(r ) =\frac{800}{r-30}+\frac{800}{r+30}

The LCD for these fractions is (r - 30)(r + 30). Thus,


		\frac{800}{r-30}+\frac{800}{r+30} \amp= \frac{800\alert{({r+30})}}{(r-30)\alert{({r+30})}}+\frac{800\blert{({r-30})}}{(r+30)\blert{({r-30})}}


		\amp = \frac{(800r + 24000) + (800r - 24000)} {(r + 30)(r - 30)}


		\amp = \frac{1600r}{r^2 - 900}
